        <h3 data-uuid="db71d6a48ea143c7944267422c35c7ca">Reform Successes</h3>
        <p data-uuid="cc25aeb748dc4b1d9fa4c4d282e42a75">A major goal of Progressive reformers was to help the urban poor. Some Progressives started settlement houses similar to Jane Addams’s Hull House. People usually started settlement houses in poor areas in order to improve education, housing, and sanitation there. Jacob Riis, a newspaper reporter, made Americans aware of the extremes of poverty suffered by working people by describing the tenement houses where immigrants lived in New York City. Riis believed that every human being deserved a decent, safe place to live. His book <i>How the Other Half Lives</i> led to reforms and new laws that improved housing conditions, such as the 1901 New York State Tenement House Act.</p>
        <section class="historical-source nobg" data-uuid="18a1be8a134e42608eda7da3cbd9a579">
            <article class="box gradient" data-uuid="1ee4e80fd71f4f1cb381809da69afa80">
                <div class="header-element" data-uuid="e50af9e9e0fa48c68920bd88b63e4929">
                    <h2 class="label" data-uuid="acbc864a7e9840468810596a4c7c2867">Historical Source</h2>
                </div>
                <div class="jonra" data-uuid="f4e507dd93514b9cb2a7f8be72f55ea1">
                    <h2 data-uuid="b22975384e844947b33f325d946667ee">The Other Half</h2>
                    <p class="source" data-uuid="08aecc1a46f34e07b8f7afe77cd7e9c1">In 1890 Jacob Riis published <i>How the Other Half Lives</i>. The book was a collection of photographs of residents and workers in New York City tenement buildings, including families and immigrants. The conditions of life that Riis showed in his photographs, like this sweatshop workplace, shocked many wealthier Americans, who then used their influence to push for reforms.</p>
                </div>
