        <p data-uuid="d3851934a7e94d859cbe635ce2d85aa2">The movement for urban reform also led to new professions. City planners helped design safer building codes and opened new public parks. Civil engineers improved transportation by paving streets and building bridges. Sanitation engineers tried to solve problems concerning pollution, waste disposal, and impure water supplies. Death rates dropped dramatically in areas where planners and engineers addressed these problems.</p>
        <p data-uuid="abe2b1754ed44aa49c386b219ac05fc5"> Progressives also believed that improving education would lead to a better society. In response to their demands, states passed laws requiring all children to attend school. Some Progressives started kindergarten programs to help young city children learn basic social skills. In 1873 reformer Susan Blow opened the first American public kindergarten in St. Louis, Missouri. In 1883 Lucy Craft Laney founded the first kindergarten for African American children in Augusta, Georgia. By 1898 more than 4,000 kindergartens had opened in the United States.</p>
        <section class="biography" data-uuid="f9778bbbb8724365b19c90e5de82dbfc">
            <div class="header-element" data-uuid="a1e74425fc5a4318a722aad92d0f9fdc">
                Biography
            </div>
            <p class="name" data-uuid="e9d1237a547b43bfbc2fa2e9d612af15">Lucy Craft Laney</p>
            <p class="date" data-uuid="5a428d3e0bcd4543ab534bac046b3fc9">1854–1933</p>
            <figure class="image-metadata bio-image" data-uuid="01505b5df1094bfaa4ed436770485053">
                <img alt="This is an artist's rendering of Lucy Craft Laney." src="../../img/module_21_lesson01/8_snlese454170_1382a.png" data-uuid="947456f379e54effae71429d7b60d439" />
                <div class="images-metadata-container" data-uuid="5e288290164d42dcab50e07c871960ba">
                    <span class="image-text image-alt"> </span>
                    <span class="image-text image-credit"> </span>
                </div>
            </figure>
            <p data-uuid="f1550b5ee9e5456e9bf8732baf9760f7">Lucy Craft Laney is considered one of Georgia’s most influential leaders in education. She was born in 1854 before slavery was abolished in the United States. Her parents, however, were free. Laney’s father had purchased his and his wife’s freedom years before Lucy was born. </p>
            <p data-uuid="5cdf524f171541c78a3cbd6ffdd0ab34">Laney was a gifted learner. She had learned to read and write by the age of 4 and by the age of 12 could translate Latin. In 1873 Laney graduated from normal school (teacher’s training) at Atlanta University. After years of teaching, “Miss Lucy,” as she was commonly known, started her own school in 1883 in a church basement in Augusta. The school was soon chartered by the state and named the Haines Normal and Industrial Institute.</p>
            <p data-uuid="da193eee694c48ceb2780e8bd2f790b1">By 1912 the Haines Institute had 34 teachers and 900 students. It was there Laney began Augusta’s first kindergarten for African American children and Augusta’s first nursing training programs for African American women.</p>
            <p data-uuid="879b6d63a8fa429786b3c5ea0e34f5fc"> Laney was very involved in other social and political reforms as well. In 1918 she helped to found the local chapter of the National Association for the Advancement of Colored People (NAACP) in Augusta and was active in the Niagara Movement with W.E.B. Du Bois.</p>
            <div class="blue-star-blue-bar" data-uuid="3cb823f953854126a641d7b5c87435a7">
                <span class="star"></span>
            </div>
        </section>
        <p data-uuid="ef5271e14a624b3b838038efec46dc85">John Dewey was a key supporter of early childhood education. His motive was to help children learn problem-solving skills, not just memorize facts. He thought this would help them in everyday life. Dewey’s teaching methods became a model for progressive education across the country.</p>
        <p data-uuid="d6310b08c0c5495db51721326971c771">Progressives also worked to improve the education of doctors and nurses. In the late 1800s there were not enough well-trained and professionally organized doctors. Researchers knew the causes of diseases such as pneumonia and tuberculosis. However, there were few medical organizations that could help spread this knowledge.</p>
        <p data-uuid="91ead5a9cf864bdeb5ea953b32f55904"> Under the leadership of Joseph McCormack, the American Medical Association (AMA) brought together local medical organizations in 1901. The AMA supported laws designed to protect public health and showed how Progressives could organize to help improve society. Other organizations followed the AMA’s lead.</p>
